<li id="cite_note-8"><b><a href="#cite_ref-8" title="">^</a></b> <cite style="font-style:normal" class="news"><a href="http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/asia-pacific/1330705.stm" class="external text" title="http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/asia-pacific/1330705.stm" rel="nofollow">"Ancient writing found in Turkmenistan."</a>. <a href="/wiki/BBC" title="BBC">BBC</a><span class="printonly">. <a href="http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/asia-pacific/1330705.stm" class="external free" title="http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/asia-pacific/1330705.stm" rel="nofollow">http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/asia-pacific/1330705.stm</a></span><span class="reference-accessdate">. Retrieved on 2008-03-30</span>.  "A previously unknown civilisation was using writing in Central Asia 4,000 years ago, hundreds of years before Chinese writing developed, archaeologists have discovered. An excavation near Ashgabat, the capital of Turkmenistan, revealed an inscription on a piece of stone that seems to have been used as a stamp seal."</cite><span class="Z3988" title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=bookitem&amp;rft.btitle=Ancient+writing+found+in+Turkmenistan.&amp;rft.atitle=&amp;rft.pub=%5B%5BBBC%5D%5D&amp;rft_id=http%3A%2F%2Fnews.bbc.co.uk%2F2%2Fhi%2Fasia-pacific%2F1330705.stm&amp;rfr_id=info:sid/en.wikipedia.org:Writing"><span style="display: none;">&#160;</span></span></li>
